Nov 12 2009 	Great base for working/ sightseeing in london	This place is really chill and in an amazing location. It's easy to get to from Heathrow on the tube (3 min walk from Earl's Ct Tube), yet it's on a quiet street. Lots of coffee shops and restaurants on Earl's Ct. road a block away. I had a really bright and airy room with own bathroom. Everything was clean. The breakfast is only cereal and toast, but there's a M&amp;S and a Tesco a block away and they're happy to store yogurts, etc in the fridge for you. And I really liked Lucianda, the proprietor, who held my key for me and buzzed me back in when I went running in Holland Park every morning. It's not the kind of place where you want to spend the whole day in your room - but it's a really nice and comfortable place to come back to in the evenings.	
Nov 9 2009 	AVERAGE LONDON BUDGET HOTEL. GOOD AREA. GOOD VALUE AND COZY ENOUGH BUT VERY POOR BREAKFAST	The Merlyn Court is located in a classy area of London - Kensington - and is very near the Victoria and Albert Museum (a must-see in London) and a few steps away from. The exteriors are very nice, it's a classical London house. All houses in this street/area have beautiful red bricks and bow windows and stuff. The hotel is welcoming in itself, full of books for guests to read, clean and tidy, though some rooms and bathrooms need a little refurbishing here and there. Although the single room on the 1st floor staircase landing has no bathroom, a sink and a mirror are inside the room: The room is quiet and comfy enough for a budget accommodation, but it's also quite cold, so you have to ask for an extra heater to cater for the hours the central heating is off. The bathroom on the same 1st floor staircase landing is very clean, but extremely uncomfortable, old, ugly and really freezing before you turn on the heat fan. We stayed at this hotel 1 year ago and got a double room with ensuite bathroom on the 1st floor, which was OK although the room was really small. On both occasions we have found the hotel to be very clean and the staff friendly. Staff are OK and helpful and so is the Italian manager, and they gladly keep food in the kitchen fridge for you or your children to have at breakfast. Which is a good idea.... considering that breakfast is actually a bit poor. Is it really that costly to add at least a glass of orange juice to the 5 pieces of cheap toast plus coffee/tea/milk and marmalade? Of course, if one wants quality, one has to pay for it and choose a different type of hotel, but considering that other similar hotels in London offer a better breakfast for the same price, I think the owner should really make an effort to improve this. Some soft music in the breakfast room would be great too, to make it a bit less 'sad'.....	
May 8 2009 	Basic average accommodations	We finished our trip with a return to London. Our first hotel was not available for this leg of the trip (4 nights), but we were able to find Merlyn Court.It offers clean, basic accomodations. The rooms are quite small (and we have stayed in small rooms). No lift. Staff was kind. I got sick during the trip. The staff made it a point to ask how I was doing, offer advice and helped when necessary. Location is good - very close to Earl's Court station, M&amp;S, and a Boots (and fast food, if you like). Even more important, very close to a couple of pubs! As 30-somethings, we liked the age range of the neighborhood. A few minuses - We had to move rooms during our stay. This meant we couldn't really settle into our room because we knew we had to move after 2 nights. They helped with the luggage thankfully, because we moved UP another floor!No TV, radio, or alarm clock in the room. Could be a good thing, especially on vacation, but I definitely felt out of touch with what was happening in the world. But I suppose that's what the metro publications are for!Lots and lots of rules posted - including no luggage on the beds. The rules made the hotel seem more &quot;hostel-ish&quot; than the other hotels we stayed out.Even with all the rules posted about not dragging luggage up/down the staircase in order to not disturb others, each morning we had kids playing in the hallways.Another good thing - easy access to Heathrow via the tube's Piccadilly line. Even with a lot of luggage among the 3 of us, we managed to make it to LHR no problem and relatively cheap!	
